<P ALIGN="CENTER"><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="GREEN"><I>Rig Veda</I>, tr. by Ralph T.H. Griffith, [1896], at sacred-texts.com</FONT></P><HR></p>  <h3 align="center" align="center">HYMN XXXVIII. Indra.</h3>  
<p>1. WIDE, Indra &#346;atakratu, spreads the bounty of thine ample grace:<br> So, Lord of fair dominion, Friend of all men, give us splendid wealth.<br> 2 The food which, Mightiest Indra, thou possessest worthy of renown<br> Is bruited as most widely famed, invincible, O Golden-hued!<br> 3 O Darter of the Stone, the powers which readily obey thy will,&#151;<br> Divinities, both thou and they, ye rule, to guard them, earth and heaven.<br> 4 And from whatever power of thine, O V&#7771;tra-slayer, it may be,<br> Bring thou to us heroic strength: thou hast a man's regard for us.<br> 5 In thy protection, with these aids of thine, O Lord of Hundred Powers,<br> Indra, may we be guarded well, Hero, may we be guarded well.</p>  
